# API Service Rules

## Location & Reuse

- Keep all frontend API request logic inside `services/` or custom hooks that call services.
- Do not call `fetch` or HTTP clients directly from page or UI components.
- Do not duplicate API calls across components — one service function per endpoint/action.

## Naming

- Use clear, action-based function names: `getListings`, `createListing`, `addToWishlist`, `submitOffer`.

## Types

- Define explicit request and response types for every service function.
- Colocate types in `types/` or next to the service; do not use untyped `any` responses.

```ts
// ❌ BAD — hardcoded URL, no types, inline in component
fetch("http://localhost:5000/api/listings").then((r) => r.json());

// ✅ GOOD — typed service, shared config, named function
import { apiClient } from "@/lib/api-client";
import type { Listing, CreateListingRequest } from "@/types/listing";

const LISTINGS = "/listings";

export async function getListings(): Promise<Listing[]> {
  return apiClient.get<Listing[]>(LISTINGS);
}

export async function createListing(data: CreateListingRequest): Promise<Listing> {
  return apiClient.post<Listing>(LISTINGS, data);
}
```

## Configuration

- Keep the base API URL in one configuration file (e.g. `lib/api-config.ts` or env-based config).
- Define endpoint path constants in the service module; do not repeat full URL strings.

## Error Handling

- Handle API errors consistently in the shared client or service layer.
- Normalize errors into a predictable shape (status, message) so hooks and UI can handle them uniformly.
- Do not swallow errors silently; rethrow or return typed error results.
